  "prompt": "Besides platinum+rhodium for NOx reduction and platinum+palladium for CO reduction, which catalyst can be used in catalytic converters?",
  "response": "In addition to platinum, rhodium, and palladium, several other materials can be used as catalysts in catalytic converters for emissions reduction:\n\n1. **Cerium oxide (CeO\u2082)**: Often added to catalytic converters to help store oxygen and improve the efficiency of the reduction and oxidation reactions.\n\n2. **Perovskite materials**: Complex oxides with the general formula ABO\u2083 (where A and B are different cations) have shown potential for use in catalytic converters due to their ability to facilitate oxygen storage and redox reactions.\n\n3. **Zeolites**: Microporous, aluminosilicate minerals can act as catalysts by providing accessible active sites and facilitating reactions with long-lived intermediates.\n\n4. **Iron-based catalysts**: These have been investigated for their cost-effectiveness and relatively good catalytic performance, especially in reducing NOx emissions.\n\n5. **Copper-based catalysts**: These can be used in specific applications and have shown potential for effectively reducing NOx emissions.\n\n6. **Nickel-based catalysts**: These are typically less expensive and can be used for certain reactions, although not as commonly employed due to issues like deactivation.\n\nThe choice of catalyst depends on various factors including the specific reactions that need to be facilitated, cost constraints, durability, and regulatory requirements for emissions.\n\n",
